<h1><i class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign"></i>IT Business Management</h1>

<p>
	Business Management provides the governance functions of the IT organisation and the management interface to the business.
	While you will find most elements of Governance in Service Management (ITIL) and in Project Management (PMBOK) and COBIT.
	The practical implementation of governance occurs in the Business Management processes and functions.
</p>
<p>The aim is to show executives how to<strong>  work with a framework to deliver business performance using a set of controls for stakeholders who hold them accountable.</strong></p>


<p>
	<%= image_tag("Governance1.png",:size => '450x320', alt: "IT Mgt" ) %>
</p>
<p>You may note that if you have problems with you controls (Service Management not working, Project Management not working) or your framework (Business and IT goals not aligned) then
	you will need to run a <%= link_to ' Business Management Remediation Program', page_path('bizopsreview')  %>.</p>


<p>
	The diagram below illustrates the high level integration of the 3 main IT Management Frameworks, Service Management, Project Management and Business Management. It leaves out the shared functions of
	Finance, HR and Vendor Management.
</p>
<p>
	<%= image_tag("SM and proj 2b.png",:size => '450x320', alt: "IT Mgt" ) %>
</p>





<p>
	Business Management uses 4 main activities to govern
	 <strong> 
	 	<ul>
		<li>Planning</li>
		<li>Reviewing</li>
		<li>Reporting</li>
		<li>Risk Management</li>
	</ul></strong> 
	
	
	<%= image_tag("bizopsprocess1.png",:size => '450x320', alt: "IT Mgt" ) %>
	
	</p>
<p>These activities correlate closely to the Plan, Do, Check, Act steps used in many business management methods.</p>
<p>
	These activities are carried out over <strong> 7 business management areas</strong> that make up the Management Framework.
</p>
